default&#xa0;default2.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe proposals will have serious consequences for the human rights of vic
defaulttims of human trafficking.
default&#xa0;
default2.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe proposals will contravene international obligations under the EU Anti-Trafficking Directive 2011/36/EU and will prevent victims of trafficking accessing support they are entitled to under the Directive.
default&#xa0;
default2.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe proposals will 
defaultdisproportionately affect victims of trafficking and will amount to discrimination on the grounds of race or national origin.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default3.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis submission is made in relation to the specific effects the proposals in the Transforming Legal Aid paper will
default have on victims of human trafficking.  Although these proposals may have similarly adverse effects on other vulnerable groups or on principles of rule of law in general, CARE’s response is focussed on the impact on one particularly marginalised group with
defaultin our society.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default4.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis proposal will obstruct access to legal assistance for victims of human trafficking
default which they are entitled to under EU Directive 2011/36/EU on preventing and combating trafficking in human beings.  Article 12(2) of the Directive states:
default&#xa0;
default4.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default“Member States shall ensure that victims of trafficking in human beings have access without delay to
default legal counselling, and, in accordance with the role of victims in the relevant justice system, to legal representation, including for the purpose of claiming compensation. Legal counselling and legal representation shall be free of charge where the victim
default does not have sufficient financial resources.”
default&#xa0;
default4.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe residence test will completely prevent some victims accessing legal counselling from a trained lawyer and for other victims it will mean a delay of up to 12 months before they can receive this 
defaultassistance.
default&#xa0;
default4.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe majority of victims of human trafficking identified in the UK come from countries outside the EEA/EU, 64.8 per cent of all victims referred to the National Referral Mechanism in 
default2012.
default  
defaultMany of these victims will fail the residence test be
defaultcause they will not have been legally resident in the UK prior to being identified as a victim.  Most traffickers will not have gone to the expense of obtaining visas and genuine travel documents for their victims.
default 
defaultAlthough an individual receives permissio
defaultn to r
defaulteside in the UK
default once they are identified as a victim
default, they would need to wait 12 months before becoming eligible for legal aid under the proposed changes.  
default&#xa0;
default4.5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe residence test will also affect v
defaultictims of trafficking who are nationals of the EEA/EU o
defaultr who have otherwise obtained legal residency in the UK
default.
default Hope for Justice, a charity which works directly with victims of trafficking has told CARE that 70 per cent of the victims they supported between April 2012 and March 2013 were EU citizens who had re
defaultsided in the UK for less than 12 months.
default&#xa0;
default4.6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe residence test will not only fail the “without delay” aspect of the EU Directive but will in some cases prevent access to justice completely.  Certain types of claim must be brought within strict time limits, w
defaulthich would expire before a victim has achieved the 12 month
defaults
default legal residence.  Victims of exploitative labour practices will be prevented from bringing claims to employment tribunals and victims 
defaultwill not be able to apply for
default judicial review of a decision r
defaultelating to their care (for example
default a decision of whether or not they are a victim of trafficking under the National Referral Mechanism).
default  
default 
default&#xa0;
default4.7.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAccess to civil legal aid is important for victims of trafficking as it 
defaultprovides a way for them to challenge incor
defaultrect decisions made by state authorities through judicial review, but it also enables victims to seek compensation from their traffickers.  
defaultCriminal prosecutions of
default those who traffic and exploit others
default 
defaultare
default vital, but ensuring victims can pursue their abusers for financial compensation is also key to providing them with justice. 
default These potential financial penalties are part of creating strong deterrents 
defaultagainst traffickers operating in this country.
default&#xa0;
default4.8.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultVictims
default of human trafficking do not have the resources to pay for a lawyer without legal aid, but also do not have the capacity to represent themselves in a foreign language, in an unfamiliar legal system.
default&#xa0;
default4.9.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCARE welcomes the proposal to create an exception to the
default residence test for asylum seekers which will apply to some victims of human trafficking.  However, not all victims of trafficking need or wish to apply for asylum.  Some are EEA citizens and others wish to return home to their own country.  This exception
default will not be available to them
default.  We believe that
default the description of asylum seekers as
default 
default“
defaultby virtue of their circumstances [...] amongst the most vulnerable in society
default,”
default could apply equally to 
defaultvictims of human trafficking
default.  Indeed, 
defaultit could be
default argue
defaultd
default that 
defaultmany are more vulnerable since 
defaultthe UK has not been a place of safety for them, rather the location of their exploitation
default.
default 
default 
defaultBy not extending an automatic exception to all individuals who are reasonably believed to be victims (having received an affirmative 
default“reasonable grounds” decision under the NRM) this proposal unjustly discriminates between victims
default who apply
default and are eligible
default for asylum and those who do not.
default&#xa0;
default4.10.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAlthough the Government claims that the residence test will not contravene obligations under the 
defaultEU Anti-
defaultT
defaultrafficking Directive
default because it will make sure legal aid will be available via an “exceptional circumstances” process 
default“where necessary to comply with obligations 
defaultunder EU or national law”
default we do not believe this will be sufficient. 
defaultW
defaultithout the adv
defaultice and assistance of a legal professional, victims of human trafficking will find it extremely difficult to comprehend and make an application for legal aid under this “exceptional circumstances” rule.  
defaultT
defaulthe proposed residence test
default even with the EU law obl
defaultigations exception
default will in 
defaulteffect
default discriminate against victims on the basis of their native language
default and nationality
default.
default&#xa0;
default4.11.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTherefore, CARE is not satisfied by these assurances and recommends instead as a minimum the proposal be amended to exempt victims of 
defaulttrafficking from the residence test.
default&#xa0;
default4.12.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCase Study:  Magdalene
defaultMagdalene is from Eastern Europe, she came to the UK determined to work her way out of backbreaking poverty. She and her children had fallen into homelessness and she was desperately searching 
defaultfor a better future for her little ones when she was approached by a man offering a better life in the UK. However, when the family arrived things were very different. Magdalene and her family were exploited for fraud and labour.  At the time of rescue Mag
defaultdalene and her family had been lawfully resident in the country for less than 12 months. Magdalene is still having problems with housing as a result of her identity documents being taken by the trafficker.  Magdalene is cooperating with a police investigat
defaultion.  If the new proposals were enacted, Magdalene and her family:
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default5.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHuman trafficking cases 
defaultpresent many challenges.  Sometimes due to language, psychological trauma or fear
default,
default victims can be reticent in sharing their stories.  For lawyers providing 
defaultthem with 
defaultassistance
default,
default determining the 
defaultfacts
default and finer legal points of an individual’s case can be a complicated and time-consuming process.
default&#xa0;
default5.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGiven that
default mistakes are made by public bodies in the decisions they take in relation to victims of trafficking, the proposal to limit payment for work on judi
defaultcial review applications is likely to result in many victims being unable to bring such cases for judicial review
default and justice not being done
default. 
defaultThe 
defaultLaw Society and the Young Legal Aid Practitioners Association have both indicated that there will be a reducti
defaulton in the willingness of solicitors to take legal aid cases due to the financial risk created by the proposal.
default  
default&#xa0;
default5.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIndividuals who have experienced trafficking and exploitation are unlikely to have the capacity to make these applications themselves due to 
defaultlimited English language and a lack of understanding of English law
default.  It is unfair that these victims should be denied access to 
defaultpursue a complaint against the state by the financial considerations imposed on a legal aid solicitor by the state
default itself
default.
default  
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default6.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe current merits test already protects the court and the legal aid budget from expending resources on cases which have little prospect of 
defaultsuccess.  Removing funding from borderline cases could have a detrimental effect on victims of human trafficking.
default&#xa0;
default6.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs has already been mentioned above, the cases of trafficking victims can be complex and the facts can be
default 
defaultunclear
default at the start
default.  This is ofte
defaultn a result of the psychological or physical d
defaultistress a victim is suffering or due to a limited grasp of English.  Under these circumstances initial assessment of the chances of success can be difficult and may mean a case is considered to be “borderline” d
defaultespite the fact that as further examination takes place the strengths of the case may emerge.
default&#xa0;
default6.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOften these complicated cases which 
defaultdraw on 
defaultintricate elements of international and domestic law 
defaultgo 
defaulton to 
defaultform precedent for subsequent cases.  It is clearly in 
defaultthe public interest for these cases to come to court in order for judges to set guidance for similar future cases.  If legal aid is removed for borderline cases, some of these 
defaultimportant cases may be excluded from court which will be detrimental to the deve
defaultlopment of judicial opinion.
default&#xa0;
default6.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs has been previously stated, victims of trafficking who have been through the terrible ordeal of trafficking and exploitation are extremely unlikely to be able to present their own case without legal understanding and in a f
defaultoreign language.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default7.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThese
default proposed changes will have very serious consequences
default for the protection of the human rights of victims of trafficking specifically the right of access to justice (European Convention on Human Rights Article 6) and the ri
defaultght not to be discriminated against (ECHR Article 14).  
default&#xa0;
default7.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFurthermore, the proposals will 
defaultcontravene key 
defaultspecific rights to which victims of trafficking are entitled under 
defaultArticle 12 of 
defaultthe EU Directive on combating trafficking in human beings.
default&#xa0;
default7.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCARE has 
defaultwelcomed the announcement by the Home Secretary that the Government plans to introduce a Modern Slavery Bill to improve the UK’s response to slavery and human trafficking.  We feel it would be a backwards step to continue to press ahead with changes to leg
defaultal aid that would so detrimentally affect those a Modern Slavery Bill would be seeking to protect.
